ğŸ”¹ Scenarios
1. ALL(Table)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Removes all filters from the table.
Acts as if the table is completely unfiltered.

Example:
Total Sales = CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]), ALL(Sales))
ğŸ‘‰ Returns sales across all customers, products, dates, even if the report has slicers.

2. ALL(Column)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Removes filters only from that column.
Other filters still apply.

Example:
Sales % of Category =
DIVIDE(
    SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]),
    CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]), ALL(Sales[Category]))
)

ğŸ‘‰ Numerator = sales for selected product,
ğŸ‘‰ Denominator = total sales of all products in that category, regardless of filter.

3. Nested with ALLEXCEPT()
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
If you want to keep some filters and ignore others, you use ALLEXCEPT().

Example:

Customer Sales Rank =
RANKX(
    ALLEXCEPT(Sales, Sales[CustomerID]),
    SUM(Sales[SalesAmount])
)

ğŸ‘‰ Ignores all filters except CustomerID.


ALLSELECTED() â†’ Respect outer filters, ignore inner filters
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Keeps slicer/page/report filters, but ignores filters applied at visual level (like categories in a bar chart).
Useful for calculating % of total in visuals.

Example:

Sales % of Total =
DIVIDE(
    SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]),
    CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[SalesAmount]), ALLSELECTED(Sales))
)


ğŸ‘‰ If you slice data to 2024 only, denominator = total sales of 2024.
ğŸ‘‰ Inside a bar chart (Product A, B, C), numerator = product sales, denominator = total sales of selected year, not full dataset.





It doesnâ€™t literally â€œpull the full table from the database,â€ but it removes the filter context inside DAX calculations.
